Dennis Hotson wrote:
&gt; On Tue, 2005-09-13 at 08:35 +0200, Bjarne Andersen wrote:
&gt; 
&gt;  &gt; With the ARFrontier every single URI is held constantly in the queue -
&gt;  &gt; with self adapting revisiting time - this means that every single URI
&gt;  &gt; holds its own information about when to be refetched. With every feth
&gt;  &gt; this &quot;waittime&quot; is lowered if the page had actually changed and raised
&gt;  &gt; if the page was the same as last time.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; The ARFrontier does not use HEAD requests at all (hope I recall right on
&gt;  &gt; this one).
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; With your approach you will have to revisit all pages (with HEAD
&gt;  &gt; requests) on a regularly basis - with some pages altered with only few
&gt;  &gt; minutes between it will be a large overhead - even though you use only
&gt;  &gt; HEAD requests (at least for some sites)
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; The check for updating is done with a simple md5 at the moment (it means
&gt;  &gt; fetching the actual content every time) - this could be altered to  use
&gt;  &gt; http-headers (even though they are not always reliable).
&gt;  &gt;
&gt; 
